Fix: In the condition where `js.indexOf('\n', pos) == -1`, we need to check if pos is at the end. If so, return null; else return substring from pos to end.

One subtlety: What if js is empty? Then pos=0, indexOf returns -1, and pos == js.length() (0) so return null is correct. Good.

Thus the fixed version:

```java
    if (js.indexOf('\n', pos) == -1) {
      if (pos >= js.length()) {
        return null;
      }
      return js.substring(pos);
    } else {
      return js.substring(pos, js.indexOf('\n', pos));
    }
```

But we also need to handle the case where `pos` is exactly at the end? pos can be equal to js.length()? After the loop, if we have found all newlines, pos may be at the end if the last line ends without newline. Then indexOf returns -1, and we should return null because pos is at end (no more characters). `pos >= js.length()` works.

Alternatively, we could use `if (pos == js.length())` but using >= is safer.

